---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<section class="hero">
				<p class="eyebrow">Build. Break. Learn.</p>
				<h1>
					Bold experiments from a curious engineer.
				</h1>
				<p class="subtitle">
					My space for building things, breaking assumptions, and learning in
					public.
				</p>
			</section>
			<div class="container">
				<section class="who">
					<h2>Who I am</h2>
					<p>
						Call me Sreeman. I grew up on Java, and the smell of build servers at 2 a.m.
						My career has been a steady march through backend systems that needed to scale,
						communicate, and not fall over when traffic spiked. The tools have changed, but the
						core obsession hasn't: how do you design software that feels boring in production
						and exciting when you're building it?
					</p>
					<p>
						E-commerce taught me the choreography of high-volume transactions and just how much
						care you need to take with inventory when people expect next-day shipping. The
						automotive aftermarket forced me to think in decades, not sprints—parts catalogs
						never die, and compatibility is a beast. Payments demanded paranoia, cryptography,
						and the humility to know every failed webhook is a customer left waiting. The food
						industry, on the other hand, tuned my instincts for latency because your dinner
						order can't wait on a noisy queue.
					</p>
					<p>
						AWS came to be a guest during my journey and then became a constant thread through those chapters
						—Lambda when it made sense, EC2 and S3 when it didn't, and until my love Kibana arrived, a toxic 
						love-hate relationship with CloudWatch logs. These days I'm channeling that experience into 
						AI adoption. I'm less excited about flashy demos and more interested in the boring plumbing 
						that lets an enterprise utilizes a model to make Go Live a peaceful day without losing sleep.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="why">
					<h2>Why this site exists</h2>
					<p>
						It's 2026 and we have more platforms than time, but none of them feel truly ours.
						This space is the antidote. No algorithms deciding who sees what, no engagement hacks,
						no performative thought leadership. Just a quiet corner of the web where I can drop
						in-progress ideas, half-formed diagrams, and the occasional rant about misused queues.
					</p>
					<p>
						I write here to remember what I've learned, to leave breadcrumbs for future-me, and
						to give anyone walking a similar path something real to grab onto. Learning in public
						is messy, but it beats waiting until something is "perfect" enough for Medium or
						LinkedIn. This site is mine, which means the experiments, the mistakes, and the wins
						get to live in one place.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="what">
					<h2>What you'll find here</h2>
					<div class="cards">
						<a class="card" href="/blog">
							<h3>Blog</h3>
							<p>
								Long-form posts on the mechanics of engineering, the realities of day-to-day 
								techincal and non technical challenges I face and learn especially adopting AI,
								and those small lessons that only show up after a production incident.
							</p>
						</a>
						<a class="card" href="/projects">
							<h3>Projects</h3>
							<p>
								A rotating shelf of things I'm building—from polished portfolio work to
								internal tools that scratched a very specific "itch".
							</p>
						</a>
						<a class="card" href="/experiments">
							<h3>Experiments</h3>
							<p>
								Rough sketches, unusual stacks, and the frameworks I'm poking at before deciding
								whether they're worth a rollout.
							</p>
						</a>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="focus">
					<h2>Current focus</h2>
					<p>
						My brain is currently looping on a single challenge: making the gap between "cool AI
						demo" and "AI system quietly running in production" vanish. That means obsessing over
						data contracts, governance that isn't a blocker, and the glue code that lets models
						play nicely with legacy systems without demanding a rewrite. Expect plenty of notes
						on adoption, tools orchestration, evaluation pipelines, and more...
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="connect">
					<h2>Get in touch</h2>
					<p>
						If something here resonates—or if you're wrestling with similar problems—reach out.
						I'd rather trade ideas than watch them rust.
					</p>
				</section>
			</div>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>

<style>
	main {
		color: rgb(var(--black));
		background: #fff;
	}

	.hero {
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--gray-gradient, #f5f7ff), rgba(var(--gray-light), 0.9)),
			rgba(var(--gray-light), 0.8);
		padding: 5rem 1.5rem 4rem;
		text-align: center;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
	}

	.hero h1 {
		font-size: 3.052em;
		max-width: 960px;
		margin: 0 auto 1rem;
		color: rgb(var(--black));
	}

	.hero .eyebrow {
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.2em;
		font-size: 0.85rem;
		color: var(--accent-dark);
		margin-bottom: 1rem;
	}

	.hero .subtitle {
		font-size: 1.25rem;
		max-width: 720px;
		margin: 0 auto;
		color: rgb(var(--gray));
	}

	.container {
		max-width: 720px;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 3rem 1.5rem 4rem;
	}

	section + section {
		margin-top: 3rem;
	}

	h2 {
		font-size: 2.441em;
		margin-bottom: 1rem;
	}

	h3 {
		font-size: 1.953em;
		margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
	}

	p {
		font-size: 1.1rem;
		line-height: 1.8;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
		margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
	}

	.cards {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
		gap: 1rem;
	}

	.card {
		display: block;
		background: #fff;
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray-light), 0.8);
		border-radius: 12px;
		padding: 1.5rem;
		text-decoration: none;
		color: inherit;
		box-shadow: 0 10px 25px rgba(15, 18, 25, 0.05);
		transition: transform 150ms ease, box-shadow 150ms ease, border-color 150ms ease;
	}

	.card:hover,
	.card:focus-visible {
		transform: translateY(-4px);
		border-color: var(--accent);
		box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(35, 55, 255, 0.1);
	}

	.card p {
		margin: 0;
	}

	.connect p {
		margin-bottom: 0;
	}

	@media (max-width: 600px) {
		.hero {
			padding: 4rem 1rem 3rem;
			text-align: left;
		}

		.hero h1 {
			font-size: 2.488em;
		}

		.hero .subtitle {
			font-size: 1.05rem;
		}
	}
</style>
